     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      15
     </xref>
     ]. The Rev-CT binding interfaces with different partners were mapped by calculating normalized per-residue chemical shift differences, Δϖ' (
     <a>
      eq. 1
     </a>
     ), that reflect cumulative chemical shift change for the backbone nuclei upon the complex formation [
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      17
     </xref>
     ]. Thus, Δϖ'~0 are expected in protein regions with no structural changes, while Δϖ'~1 reflect binding-induced conformational rearrangements accompanied by significant chemical shift variations.
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 3A
     </xref>
     shows the comparison Δϖ' values between Rev1-CT and its complex with polη-RIR peptide obtained in the absence (blue) and presence of Rev7/Rev3 (green), while
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 3B
     </xref>
     displays Δϖ' for Rev1-CT domain obtained upon binding Rev7/Rev3 (red) and polη-RIR motif (blue) plotted
