    <title>
     3.3. Rev7 binding triggers changes in Rev1-CT structure and dynamics
    </title>
    <p>
     The chemical shifts of Rev1-CT and its complexes were used to assess changes in secondary structure and conformational flexibility of the domain upon binding its partners [
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      20
     </xref>
     ,
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      21
     </xref>
     ].
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 4A
     </xref>
     shows secondary structure of the isolated Rev1-CT and its complexes with fragments of one (Rev7/Rev3) and two (Rev7/Rev3/polη) TLS polymerases predicted from the backbone chemical shifts by TALOS+ [
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      20
     </xref>
     ], while
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 4B
     </xref>
     displays order parameters, S
     <sup>
      2
     </sup>
     , for the backbone amide groups predicted by RCI [
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      21
     </xref>
     ], where S
     <sup>
      2
     </sup>
     =1(0) corresponds to restricted(unconstrained) dynamics. It is clear that neither secondary structure nor backbone flexibility of the domain are affected by interaction with Rev7/Rev3 and/or polη-RIR, with the exception of the C-terminal part (residues 1246–1251) undergoing remarkable transformation upon Rev7 binding. This region, flexible in isolated Rev1-CT, is stabilized in complexes with Rev7/Rev3 and Rev7/Rev3/polη-RIR (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 4B
     </xref>
     ) and adopts an extended β-strand conformation (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 4A
     </xref>
     ). Previous mutational analysis identified β-strands β8' and β8'' of Rev7 as interaction site for Rev1-CT domain (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 4C
     </xref>
     ) [
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      14
     </xref>
     ]. Specifically, mutations of L186 of β8' and Q200, Y202 of β8'' on the outer surface of 5-stranded β-sheet of Rev7 were shown to decrease Rev1-CT binding. Our results indicate that the C-terminal residues 1246–1251 of Rev1-CT may provide an extension of the β-sheet of Rev7 by forming an additional β-strand that interacts with β8' (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 4C
     </xref>
     ). On the other hand, residues 1201–1204 from H2–H3 loop and α-helix H3 of Rev1-CT, exhibiting pronounced chemical shift changes upon Rev7 binding (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Fig. 3B,C
     </xref>
     ), may provide docking site for the outer surface of the Rev7 β-sheet.
